AB  - Negative abnormal stock returns of about 1% occur near
                                                record dates of stock splits. Further, the lower the
                                                returns, the more positive are ex-date returns and
                                                when-issued premiums. A possible explanation of
                                                these related phenomena is that trading hindrances
                                                associated with record dates create trading
                                                inconvenience that is reflected in lower prices near
                                                record dates. In turn, anomalous positive ex-date
                                                returns arise in part from the abnormally low prices
                                                of unsplit shares caused by the negative record date
                                                returns.
